spotlighting strategies that facilitate continuity through family transmission, theatre, activism, publishing, song, cinema, and other new media. Rebecca Margolis uses a multidisciplinary approach that draws on methodologies from history, sociolinguistics, ethnography, digital humanities, and screen studies to examine the ways in which engagement with Yiddish has evolved across multiple planes.Investigating the products of an abiding dedication to cultural continuity among successive generations, Yiddish Lives On offers innovative approaches to the preservation, promotion, and revitalization of minority, heritage, and lesser-taught languages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewsxLanguages. 0aLanguage and culture. 0aYiddish languagexSocial aspects. 0aYiddish language. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aCanadian Jewish Congress.  aChava Rosenfarb.  aDavid Roskies.  aDora Wasserman.  aHasidic Yiddish.  aHasidim.  aHolocaust literature.  aHolocaust.  aJewish People’s and Peretz Schools (JPPS).  aJewish Public Library.  aJewish new media.  aKlezKanada.  aKlezmer music.  aLeon Leybl Botwinik.  aLess Commonly Taught Languages (LLCL).  aMontreal.  aPeretz Centre for Jewish Culture.  aQueer Yiddishkeit.  aToronto.  aVancouver.  aYidLife Crisis.  aYiddishism.  aYiddishkayt.  aYiddishland.  aYugntruf.  achildhood bilingualism.  acommunity choirs.  aendangered languages.  aforeign-language cinema.  aheritage languages.  aheterotopic Yiddishland.  alanguage revitalization.  alanguage revival.  alinguicide.  amulticulturalism.  anew Yiddish cinema.  apostvernacular Yiddish.  asecular Jewish schools.  asecular Yiddish.  atransvernacular Yiddish.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831112